After I cancel his second and third spell, Peter finally figures out what I'm doing and he stops using any of his complicated spells, limiting himself only to the simplest and most basic type of magic in his repertoire, so that he won't give me enough time to use my dispelling technique before he finishes his casting. I try in vain to predict his next few spells, but I soon realize that there's no point in using this tactic anymore. I might as well just fight him with regular spells, because right now I'm not making any meaningful contributions to this battle.

Just as I am about to fly closer to Peter, I feel two ropes tying themselves tightly around my ankles, and then not even a second later, two other ropes bind themselves around my wrists as well, pulling my arms behind my back. When I turn my head around, I realize that the four ropes had been conjured from below me while I wasn't looking. 

 I was so focused on their battle that it didn't even cross my mind to check my surroundings. Was this his plan all along? To distract me with his fight against the Overseer while secretly using conjuration magic to make these restraints appear out of nowhere? Damn it, if only I could move my arms a little, I might be able to burn the ropes with a fire spell or something. I'm not at a level where I can cast spells without moving my arms, yet. Isn't there some spell that requires me to only move my fingers which could be helpful in this situation? What about the Overseer? Maybe he can get me out of this! I need to call out to him.

"Hey, Overseer, can you help--"

"Time's up," Peter says, before I get the time to finish my sentence, and then he uses my initial lightning spell against me, making me lose my consciousness in a matter of seconds.

