 Since I could pretty much guess what spell he was going to use before he even started moving his hands, I easily managed to cast the spell in reverse and to dispel it before he could finish his motions. That being said, there is no way for me to dispel the box itself, so the drone is still trapped, even if it is no longer in mortal danger.

"Unfortunately, the Overseer protocol is unable to free itself from its captivity or cast spells outside of the box without the use of its experimental features,"  the green-eyed drone says. "The Overseer apologizes for the inconvenience, and hopes that the current circumstances will not negatively impact the rating you will give it in the end-of-month survey."

"Don't worry, Overseer, I got you covered!" I say. "No matter what spell he casts while you're inside that box, I'm pretty confident that I can dispel it."

As I am saying these words, Peter gives me one long look, and he just stands there for about ten seconds, contemplating on what I've said.

"What's the matter, Peter?" I say. "Did you give up already?"

"No..." Peter says. "But I think it's safe to say that I might have been underestimating you a little bit, until now. After thinking things over for a short while, I realized that you are for all intents and purposes a mage and a generalist in this realm, and maybe I should start treating you as such. Tell me, Barry, have you ever seen a fight between Brinhorn and Azarius?"

 "Yeah, I did see a few of those," I say. "Brinhorn always used to insist on me coming to watch his official matches while I was still apprenticing under him."

"Apprenticing under Brinh--" Peter begins to say, but then he interrupts himself, as he closes his eyes and starts to massage his forehead with his fingers. "Never mind. I don't care if you actually were that man's apprentice or not. The point I was trying to make is that whenever two generalists fight, they have a certain way of doing battle that is not comparable to any other kinds of mage fights. Do you know what I'm talking about?"

"I mean, yeah, it would have been pretty hard to not see the difference," I say.

"Good," Peter says. "I only had the opportunity to see one of their duels, due to how insanely hard it is to obtain permission to leave Varathia as an Ollendor citizen, but that one duel will remain imprinted in my mind forever."

While Peter is talking, I can slowly feel the whole world beginning to spin around me, as if I'd just gulped down an entire bottle of dwarven ale.

"As a former apprentice of Brinhorn, I'm sure that you will immediately recognize the famous battle that I am about to recreate before your eyes. Let us see if you can live up to your old mentor's teachings."

}
