ID: B3-Ch09b-Counter
TEXT:

 Instead of trying to counter his spell, I decide to wait, and to pay close attention to what my enemy is doing. I know this is risky, but my gut is telling me that he is trying to trick me again, somehow.

As I closely observe Peter, one thing about him in particular strikes me as odd. He is trying to make it seem like he's looking straight at me, but he keeps throwing short glances at something below me every now and then while he is casting his spell. When I look below me as well, in order to see what he was so preoccupied with, I notice four ropes that are getting longer and longer, and moving towards me.

"You bastard!" I tell Peter, as I do some quick movements with my hands and then send a burst of flames to burn all of the ropes. "You were trying to fool me again, weren't you? You were just faking the freezing rain spell so that you could keep me distracted and tie me with the ropes! Do you think I'm stupid or something?"

"No," Peter says, as he now stops pretending to cast the ice rain spell. "But I was hoping that you'd at least take a few more seconds to figure it out. I think it's safe to say that I've been underestimating you a little bit. You are for all intents and purposes a mage and a generalist in this realm, and I should treat you as such. Tell me, Barry, have you ever seen a fight between Brinhorn and Azarius?"

 "Yeah, I did see a few of those," I say. "Brinhorn always used to insist on me coming to watch his official matches while I was still apprenticing under him."

"Apprenticing under Brinh--" Peter begins to say, but then he interrupts himself, as he closes his eyes and starts to massage his forehead with his fingers. "Never mind. I don't care if you actually were that man's apprentice or not. The point I was trying to make is that whenever two generalists fight, they have a certain way of doing battle that is not comparable to any other kinds of mage fights. Do you know what I'm talking about?"

"I mean, yeah, it would have been pretty hard to not see the difference," I say.

"Good," Peter says. "I only had the opportunity to see one of their duels, due to how insanely hard it is to obtain permission to leave Varathia as an Ollendor citizen, but that one duel will remain imprinted in my mind forever."

While Peter is talking, I can slowly feel the whole world beginning to spin around me, as if I'd just gulped down an entire bottle of dwarven ale.

"As a former apprentice of Brinhorn, I'm sure that you will immediately recognize the famous battle that I am about to recreate before your eyes. Let us see if you can live up to your old mentor's teachings."

choice("Continue", B3-Ch09b-Balance, v_current_scene = B3-Ch09b-Balance)


ID: B3-Ch09b-Balance
TEXT:

 My sense of balance has been completely thrown off. I feel like I'm about to puke. I didn't even know you could have these sensations in an immaterial plane of existence such as this.

That being said, Peter has been kind enough to notify me in advance of what spell he was going to use against me, so I'm not planning to betray his expectations. Recalling the exact spells that Brinhorn cast to get himself out of this situation in one of his duels against Azarius, I begin by making flames come out of my hands, and then I use my palms like hot irons to burn both of my cheeks for a few seconds. As I struggle to endure the excruciating pain from my burnt face, I quickly conjure two boulders in the air on both sides of me, and I use them to smack myself in the face from both sides, right on the burn marks.

When I'm done with that, I create a bucketful of freezing-cold water above my head, and I let it drop on top of me, drenching my entire body in the icy liquid. While I am still trembling from the cold, I point towards Peter with my right hand and then I spin my index-finger counter-clockwise, while I imagine some invisible earplugs dropping from his ears.

 "Astounding..." Peter says, with what appears to be genuine amazement in his voice, as he is slowly clapping, while I am still trying to stop my body from shaking violently. "I was half-joking when I told you to live up to your old mentor's teachings, but I never expected you to go this far. You actually reproduced every single one of Brinhorn's spells from the beginning of that battle, including the rare variant of his dispelling technique that he used to get rid of Azarius' protection against his own sonic attacks."

"Yes, w-w-well, I was the o-o-one who taught him that dispelling technique a-a-after all!" I say, trying my best to sound tough, even though I'm still trembling like crazy from the cold.

"I must admit that I didn't think you would go through with it, even if you knew the spells that you needed to cast," Peter says. "Seeing you inflict so much damage upon yourself without hesitation in the same way that Brinhorn did in that match makes me wonder if some of his craziness rubbed off on you or if it was in fact the other way around..."

