ID: B3-Ch09b-Versatile
TEXT:

#if(v_b3_ch9_backup == 0) {
 "I'm really glad to see how well you two are getting along," the king of the underground says loudly, from a distance, as he is still busy building barriers around himself to defend from Flower, who is attacking him from all possible angles, trying to find a weak spot in his defenses, "but maybe you could hurry it up just a little, Peter?... I can barely hold off this ethereal girl on my own with how weak my aura is in this realm. Surely, you don't want to have to fight both her and Barry at the same time, do you?"

"No, my king..." Peter says. "I will try my best to hasten things on my end."

"And how exactly are you planning to do that?" I ask Peter. "Just to be clear, your trick with the invisible ear plugs won't work a second time. If you want to cast that sonic spell again, you'd better be prepared to dunk yourself in cold water afterwards."

"Have you already forgotten that we're supposed to be reenacting one of the battles between Brinhorn and Azarius?" Peter says. "We've barely even recreated the first few seconds of that fight so far. There is so much more that we need to do."

}
#if(v_b3_ch9_backup == 0 || v_b3_ch9_backup == 1) {
 "Well, it's not like I had much choice in the matter," I answer him, having finally stopped my trembling. "That sonic attack you did just now is too high-pitched to be perceived by our ears, but its effects are almost impossible to dispel unless you are a highly-skilled, specialized white mage. That is probably one of the reasons why Azarius enjoys sonic spells so much. They are incredibly versatile and ridiculously hard to counter through normal means. Brinhorn might not have given me much reason to genuinely look up to him during the time we've spent together, but I will say that this one particular way he chose to counter Azarius' spell was nothing short of genius."

"It was, indeed..." Peter says, looking as if he were reminiscing over a time long past. "It felt so stupid when I saw it at the time, and yet it was so effective, in its simplicity. Why bother with countering the effects of a complicated sound pressure spell that directly targets your inner ear and messes up your sense of balance, when you can just use tried-and-true, age-old methods that dwarves have been using to get out of their drunken stupors for hundreds of years! I have to say... that fight was truly a sight to behold!"

 "You've seen how far I'm willing to go to reproduce Brinhorn's exact spells from that fight and you still want to continue?" I say. "I'm having a hard time figuring out if you're being stupidly brave, or just plain stupid."

"And I'm having a hard time seeing how you can be so confident in your victory, when you should already know all too well who won the fight that we're now copying," Peter says. "I'll give you a hint. It's the same person who's won every single time since those two started having their duels."

"Just because we're doing a reenactment doesn't mean that I can't go off-script just a tiny bit," I say. "Don't worry, you'll get to see the source of my confidence soon enough."

"Let's see it, then," Peter says, and then he begins to attack me in the same way that Azarius attacked Brinhorn all those years ago.

}
