ID: B3-Ch09b-Guarantee
TEXT:

 I am now finding myself surrounded by a hundred or so manticores, which are flying around me from all directions, including directly below me. I already know from the battle between Brinhorn and Azarius that the majority of these are supposed to be illusions, but in the original fight, five of the winged lions were real and Azarius was also hiding amongst them, shapeshifted as a manticore while waiting for the ideal moment to strike.

Just like in the battle that we are copying, Peter has managed to successfully cast an illusion spell, a summoning spell and a shapeshifting spell almost simultaneously, without giving me much time to react. The fact that he managed to cast all three spells without making any movements at all caught me completely off-guard. He must have been secretly preparing the spells while I was being distracted by our previous conversation.

Unfortunately, while I was initially able to track which were the real manticores and which were the illusions, it has gotten harder and harder for me to tell them apart as they've been shuffling their positions constantly for the past twenty seconds. Similarly to what Azarius did against Brinhorn, Peter is in no hurry to attack me, because he knows that the more time passes, the more I will doubt myself on which of the flying monsters I need to defend myself from and which I'll need to ignore.

 The spells that Brinhorn used to get out of this predicament are complicated, and I've never had the opportunity to practice them before, but they're the best option I've got. At least I know the theory behind them, so I'll just have to do my best to figure out the magical flow patterns based on the knowledge I already have. Let's give this a shot.

As the manticores are still circling around me, trying to get me confused, I take advantage of the short respite that my enemy has granted me to quickly test several flow patterns that I've noticed in the past, through my many years of studying magical theory. Once I find the motions that seem to work, I visualize all of the magical particles in my head and I guide them on their path, while I play around with different levels of magical intensity until the flow reacts positively to my aura.

The first spell that I cast is one that temporarily enhances my sight and focus, similarly to the Observation stat from my stat device, which I am not carrying with me in this immaterial realm. As soon as my power of observation increases, I immediately confirm which of the manticores are real, because they are the only ones that are deviating from the general trajectory that the majority of the other manticores are following. My greater focus also makes it easier to keep an eye on Peter, whom I've been monitoring closely ever since he shapeshifted.

Now that I don't need to worry about losing sight of the summoned manticores anymore, I can finally concentrate on winning this battle.

 The question is... should I continue to copy what Brinhorn did, or should I do something else? So far Peter has been reproducing the battle perfectly, but there's no guarantee that he'll do it until the end. At a certain point, he's bound to deviate from the original fight in some way and maybe it would be better if I made the first move rather than-- okay, never mind, too late for that. Peter is now diving straight for me in his manticore form. Azarius never did anything like this against Brinhorn. 

Is he going to transform back into his human form and cast a spell at me once he gets closer?... No, no, no, the shapeshifting process can't be done instantly, and it would leave him too vulnerable. Then is he planning to attack me while he's in his manticore form instead? Something doesn't add up, here. This has to be one of his traps again! I can feel it... I think he's trying to goad me into attacking him. Let's see if he'll reveal his cards to me if I play along a little.

I get into a stance and I pretend that I'm about to cast a short-range paralysis spell on him as soon as he gets closer. Okay, this should be convincing enough. Come on, Peter, show me what you're--

Before I even get to finish my thought process, the image of the manticore in front of me disappears, and it is replaced by Peter, who had apparently never shapeshifted in the first place, and only used illusion magic to make me think that he did. Just as he casts a paralysis spell of his own, I use my air currents to dash away from him and to narrowly avoid his attack. 

